==Second-level divisions==
:''See [[List of second-level administrative divisions of North Korea]] for a complete list.
[[File:NKorea county map 2012.png|thumb|right|300px|A map of North Korea with second-level divisions]]
The most common second-level division is the county (''Kun''; {{lang|ko|[[Hangul|군]]}}, {{lang|ko|[[Hanja|郡]]}}), a less urbanized area within a province or directly governed city.  The more populous districts within provinces are cities (''Si''; {{lang|ko|[[Hangul|시]]}}, {{lang|ko|[[Hanja|市]]}}), and the city of [[Nampho]] is a special city (''T'ŭkkŭpsi''; {{lang|ko|[[Hangul|특급시]]}}, {{lang|ko|[[Hanja|特級市]]}}).  Some provinces also have two types of districts (''Ku'', ''Chigu'').

The city centers of the directly governed cities are organized into wards (''Kuyŏk'', equivalent to [[Administrative divisions of South Korea|South Korea]]n ''Gu'').

==Third-level divisions==<!-- This section is linked from [[Demographics of North Korea]] -->
Rural parts of cities and counties are organized into villages (''Ri'', {{lang|ko|{{linktext|리|, |里|}}}}).  The downtown areas within cities are divided into neighborhoods (''[[Dong (administrative division)|Tong]]'', {{lang|ko|{{linktext|동|, |洞|}}}}), and a populous part of a county forms a town (''Ŭp'', {{lang|ko|{{linktext|읍|, |邑|}}}}).  Some counties also have workers' districts (''Rodongjagu'', {{lang|ko|{{linktext|로동자구|, |勞動者區|}}}}).

