[[Image:Antonio Snider-Pellegrini Opening of the Atlantic.jpg|thumb|250px|right|In 1858, Snider-Pellegrini made these two maps.  They depict his interpretation of how the American and African continents may once have fit together before becoming separated.]]

'''Antonio Snider-Pellegrini''' (1802–1885) was a French [[geographer]] and scientist who theorized about the possibility of [[continental drift]], anticipating [[Alfred Wegener|Wegener's]] theories concerning [[Pangaea]] by several decades.

In 1858, Snider-Pellegrini published his book, ''La Création et ses mystères dévoilés'' ("The Creation and its Mysteries Unveiled").  He proposed that all of the [[continents]] were once connected together during the [[Pennsylvanian Period]].  He based this theory on the fact that he had found [[fossil|plant fossils]] in both Europe and the United States that were identical. He found matching fossils on all of the continents.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/brca/forteachers/plateact3.htm Plate Tectonics Theory, National Park Service: for Teachers]</ref>

Also Pellegrini proposed a large change in the Earth’s size during the time of the Biblical Genesis account.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Scalera, Giancarlo|title=Roberto Mantovani (1854-1933) and his ideas on the expanding Earth, as revealed by his correspondence and manuscripts|journal=Annals of Geophysics|volume=52|issue=6|page=617|date=2 Dec 2009|url=http://www.annalsofgeophysics.eu/index.php/annals/article/view/4622}}</ref>

