[[File:Pitcairn.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The "Petroglyphs" is marked on the southeast coast.]]
'''Down Rope''' is a coastal area on the southeast coast of [[Pitcairn Island]] in the south Pacific,<ref name="HinzHoward2006">{{cite book|last1=Hinz|first1=Earl R.|last2=Howard|first2=Jim|title=Landfalls of Paradise: Cruising Guide to the Pacific Islands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CjIg5FgUUW8C&pg=PA123|accessdate=30 April 2012|date=1 May 2006|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3037-3|page=123}}</ref> to the east of the [[Aute Valley]] and north of [[Break Jim Hip]], it lies on the eastern side of an inlet and contains large petroglyphs on the rock face, testament to the Polynesian settlers of centuries ago.<ref name="McKinnon2009">{{cite book|last=McKinnon|first=Rowan|title=South Pacific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IfugqkV_udYC&pg=PA617|accessdate=30 April 2012|date=1 August 2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-786-8|pages=244–5}}</ref> It is described as "a steep cliff located on the southern coast south of [[Ned Young's Ground]], and west of [[St Paul's Point]]. At its foot, despite its perilous descent, is a popular picnic area and Pitcairn's only beach."{{cn|date=September 2015}} The descent from the cliff top is said to be "spine chilling".<ref name="Carlsson2000">{{cite book|last=Carlsson|first=Susanne Chauvel|title=Pitcairn: island at the edge of time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ft1AAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=2000|publisher=Central Queensland University Press|isbn=978-1-875998-92-0|page=83}}</ref> There is anchorage at Down Rope and [[ignimbrite]] is also found in the vicinity.<ref name="Stanley2004">{{cite book|last=Stanley|first=David|title=Moon Handbooks South Pacific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EDGapfBX-CAC&pg=PA293|accessdate=30 April 2012|date=3 December 2004|publisher=David Stanley|isbn=978-1-56691-411-6|page=293}}</ref><ref name="BentonSpencer1995">{{cite book|last1=Benton|first1=Tim|last2=Spencer|first2=Tom|title=The Pitcairn Islands: biogeography, ecology and prehistory : proceedings of an international discussion meeting held at the Linnean Society, 5-6 May 1994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WAEUAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2012|year=1995|publisher=Linnean Society of London, Published for the Linnean Society of London by Academic Press|isbn=978-0-12-089345-4|page=342}}</ref>

