'''James M. Rubenstein''' (born 1949) is an American [[geographer]] and Professor of Geography at [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]], known for his work on human geography<ref>Samovar, Larry, Richard Porter, and Edwin McDaniel. ''Communication between cultures.'' Cengage Learning, 2009.</ref> and specifically on the US [[automotive industry]].<ref>Holmes, Thomas J. "Localization of industry and vertical disintegration." ''Review of Economics and Statistics'' 81.2 (1999): 314-325.</ref>
Rubenstein obtained his B.A. ïn public affairs from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1970, and went to London where he obtained his MSc in city and regional planning from the [[London School of Economics]] in 1971. Back in the States he obtained his PhD in geography and human engineering from the [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 1975.<ref>Klier, Thomas H., and James M. Rubenstein. ''Who really made your car?: restructuring and geographic change in the auto industry.'' WE Upjohn Institute, 2008. p. 397</ref> Rubenstein is appointed Professor of Geography at [[Miami University]]. He also works as consultant in the research department at the [[Federal Reserve Bank]] of Chicago.
== Selected publications == * Rubenstein, James M. ''Making and selling cars: Innovation and change in the US automotive industry.'' JHU Press, 2001. * Rubenstein, James M. ''Changing US Auto Industry.'' Routledge, 2002. * Rubenstein, James M., and Jerome Donald Fellmann. ''The Cultural Landscape: An Introduction to Human Geography.'' (2004). * Klier, Thomas H., and James M. Rubenstein. ''Who really made your car?: restructuring and geographic change in the auto industry.'' WE Upjohn Institute, 2008.
