In [[Rabelais]]' ''[[Gargantua and Pantagruel]]'', '''Ruach''' is the Isle of Winds. The people of Ruach eat and drink nothing but wind, and live inside [[weathercock]]s. The island is an [[allegory]] of the insubstantial promises and flatteries that people must subsist on to survive in this world.

The word "Ruach" comes from the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] meaning "spirit", "wind", "breath", or "air".  The Greek equivalent is "pneuma" and the Latin is "spiritus".

